portFacilities.text: ISPS compliant. Container Security Initiative (CSI) designated port

EUROGEUL CHANNEL:
The Eurogeul Channel which is entered N of Euro Light Buoy (51° 58' N; 3° 10' E) is 25 nautical miles long, 600 m wide, direction 082.5°, depth reducing from 24.5 m to 24.0 m MLLWS and is dedicated to vessels with a draft of 17.84-22.55 m. The Eurogeul Channel starts 1.4 miles W of the Euro 1 buoy. It is flanked on both sides by dredged areas 300 m wide in depth of 22.0 m MLLWS. Once in the Eurogeul Channel a vessel can turn halfway in the turning basin between buoys E7 and E9. The turning basin diameter is 2700 m in depth of 24.3 m MLLWS. In emergencies this turning basin can also serve as an anchorage for vessels with a draught up to 21.35 m
Crossing the Eurogeul Channel (which should be done without interfering with traffic):
northbound between E5 and E7 light buoys in pos 51° 59' N; 3° 28' E
southbound between E3 and E5 light buoys in pos 51° 59' N; 3° 23' E
MAAS CENTER BUOY:
The Maas Center Buoy is where the Eurogeul Channel ends and the Maasgeul Channel starts
MAASGEUL CHANNEL:
The Maasgeul Channel is 6 miles long with the width reducing from 600 m at the Maas Center Buoy to 500 m at the harbour entrance, direction 112.0°, depth 23.4 m MLLWS. In the event of an emergency, and before entering the Maasgeul Channel, a deep draught vessel can anchor in the emergency anchorage area situated to the NE of the Maas Center Buoy, or use this area as a turning basin. Vessels of more than 14.3 m draught cannot meet or overtake each other in this channel
FAIRWAYS:
Nieuwe Waterweg: After leaving the Maasgeul Channel, the Splitsingsdam separates the Nieuwe Waterweg from the Calandkanaal. The Splitsingsdam is a separation mole. The centre line of the entrance to the river Nieuwe Maas is 107.0° and indicated by red leading lights. Min depth of 14.2 m MLLWS. An anti-flood barrier has been constructed across the Nieuwe Waterweg approx 2 miles upstream from the leading light at Berghaven. This will close when a water height is predicted of at least 3.0 m + NAP in Rotterdam. Free passage is possible up to 2 h before closure
Nieuwe Maas: The Nieuwe Waterweg river becomes the Nieuwe Maas river with minimum depths of 13.8 m MLLWS up to Waalhaven, from Waalhaven to Erasmusbrug is 10.85 m MLLWS and after Erasmusbrug is 6.85 m MLLWS
Calandkanaal: The direction of the entrance to the Calandkanaal and Beerkanaal is 116.0°, the central line is indicated by green leading lights. Min depth of 22.75 m MLLWS
Beerkanaal: Entry to the Europoort area is via the Beerkanaal. The direction of 192.5° is indicated by green leading lights. Min depth of 22.6 m MLLWS
Oude Maas: When passing the Oude Maas the Botlek bridge and the Spijkenisse bridge must be passed. Permission is required to navigate this river for sea-going vessels with an loa of 175 m or over, a beam over 25 m and if the draught is over 8.8 m (in fresh water) for vessels proceeding to Dordrecht or 8 m for vessels proceeding to Moerdijk. Permission must be requested via Vessel Traffic & Operations 24 h prior to arrival. Min depth in Oude Maas is 9.6 m MLLWS to Spui and then afterwards 9.4 m MLLWS

Anchorage Area 1: in pos 52° 07' N; 2° 45' E in depth of 28.5 m MLLWS - long term anchorage (entering Eurogeul channel after 24 h), for vessels with a draught from 17.4 m up to 22.55 m
Anchorage Area 2: in pos 51° 56' N; 2° 57' E in depth of 27.2 m MLLWS - short term anchorage (entering Eurogeul channel within 24 h), for vessels with a draught from 17.4 m up to 22.55 m
Anchorage Area 3A: in pos 52° 00' N; 3° 20' E in depth of 24.5 m MLLWS - for vessels that cannot anchor in No's 4 or 5 anchorage areas because of their draught. Max draught is 17.4 m
Anchorage Area 3B: in pos 52° 02' N; 3° 36' E in depth of 20.7 m MLLWS - for LNG carriers only
Anchorage Area 3C: in pos 51° 57' N; 3° 18' E in depth of 23.0 m MLLWS - for vessels that cannot anchor in No's 4 or 5 anchorage areas because of their draught. Max draught is 17.4 m (anchorage area 3A is preferred over anchorage area 3C)
Anchorage Area 4A: in pos 51° 56' N; 3° 45' E in depth of 11.6 m MLLWS - for vessels approaching from the west and south
Anchorage Area 4BN: in pos 51° 55' N; 3° 31' E in depth of 14.3-21.0 m MLLWS - for vessels approaching from the west and south
Anchorage Area 5A: in pos 52° 08' N; 3° 48' E in depth of 18 m MLLWS - for vessels approaching from the north and north west
Emergency anchorage area for deep draught vessels: in pos 52° 00' N; 3° 34' E in depth of 24.4 m MLLWS - for emergencies only
Emergency anchorage area for deep draught vessels: in pos 52° 02' N; 3° 56' E in depth of 24.7 m MLLWS - for emergencies only

The pilotage authority for the port is the Regional Pilots Corporation Rotterdam-Rijnmond. The pilots are supported by their company Loodswezen Nederland BV (www.loodswezen.nl)
The pilot service for the Rotterdam-Rijnmond area includes Europoort, Rotterdam, Vlaardingen, Schiedam, Maassluis, Dordrecht and Moerdijk
Pilot Stations:
Boarding station for vessels with draught up to 14.29 m is either:
a) by small or large tender 4 miles WSW of Maas Center Buoy in pos 51° 59' N; 3° 47.2' E (1 pilot boarding)
b) by helicoptor for vessels coming from the north: in the southbound lane of TSS Maas North, exact position will be advised via VTS (1 pilot boarding)
c) by helicoptor for vessels coming from the west: in the eastbound lane of TSS Maas West Inner/Outer, exact position will be advised via VTS (1 pilot boarding)
Boarding station for vessels with draught between 14.3 m and 17.39 m is by small or large tender or helicoptor W of the E13 Buoy, in the Eurogeul, exact position will be advised via VTS (1 pilot boarding)
Boarding station for vessels with draught between 17.4 m and 22.55 m is at rendezvous point 51° 59' N; 3° 00.0' E (2 pilots boarding)
Deep Sea Pilotage is provided by Dirkzwager's Coastal & Deep Sea Pilotage, Tel: +31 10 593 1600, Fax: +31 10 592 5767, Email: info@dirkmail.com, Website: www.dirkzwager.com, and must be ordered 48 h before arrival at one of the following pilot stations:
a) usual point of rendezvous Brixham is 1.5 nautical miles E of Berry Head or 4.5 nautical miles E of Berry Head for vessels with draught of 17.4 m and above
b) usual point of rendezvous Cherbourg is 1 nautical mile E of CH-1 buoy or 7 nautical miles N of the breakwaters for tankers. Also tankers and other deep draught vessels can embark the pilot by helicoptor in the following positions:
R/V position Alpha, 13 nautical miles N of Cap de la Hague
R/V position Bravo, 10 nautical miles N of Cap Levy

The Rotterdam Vessel Traffic System (VTS) area extends for 38 nautical miles seawards of the port entrance to 2 nautical miles E of the Van Brienenoord Bridge and 4 nautical miles E of the Spijkenisse Bridge across the Oude Maas river, including all adjacent harbour basins. The VTS area is divided into 12 sectors, each with its own dedicated VHF channel
Sector Maas Approach - VHF Channel  1
Sector Pilot Maas - VHF Channel  2
Sector Maas Entrance - VHF Channel  3
Sector Rozenburg, including 'Breeddiep' - VHF Channel 65
Sector Europoort - VHF Channel 66
Sector Maassluis - VHF Channel 80
Sector Botlek - VHF Channel 61
Sector Oude Maas - VHF Channel 62
Sector Eemhaven - VHF Channel 63
Sector Waalhaven - VHF Channel 60
Sector Maasbruggen - VHF Channel 81
Sector Brienenoord - VHF Channel 21

In a period of 24 h there are two high waters and two low waters, with different amplitudes. A special phenomenon manifests itself at Hook of Holland, which has a double low tide with the second low water lower than the first. On the river mean tidal range is 1.7 m and spring tidal range is 1.8 m
Port Hospital, Tel: +31 10 404 3300, Fax: +31 10 412 1517. All facilities available

(1) Bulk minerals by European Bulk Services (E.B.S.) B.V.: Monday 0730 until Saturday 1530 continuously with meal breaks of 30 mins/shift
Agribulk by European Bulk Services (E.B.S.) B.V.: Monday 0730 until Saturday 1530 continuously with meal breaks of 30 mins/shift. In principle no work is performed on Saturday nights, Sundays and official holidays
Overtime during weekends and holidays to be agreed with the management. Labourers are only available on a voluntary basis
(2) Containers: The large container terminals operate around the clock, weekends inclusive
No work is permitted from Dec 24 at 1530 to Dec 26 at 0715 and from Dec 31 at 1530 to Jan 1 at 1515
(3) General Cargo: Day shift 0730-1600. Evening shift 1600-0015. Night shift 0000-0730
Normal working hours are during the day shifts and the evening shifts on Monday to Friday as well as the day shift on Saturday. Generally gangs will be allocated on basis 2 for the day shift/1 for the evening shift
Overtime: For the night shift has to be paid, as well as for work on Sundays and holidays, starting as from the end of the day shift on the preceding day until the beginning of the day shift on the next day
(4) Oil: At the refineries of Shell, ChevronTexaco, Esso, Kuwait Petroleum Europoort (KPE) and BP tankers discharging is continuous including weekends without extra charge. This also applies to the Maasvlakte Oil Terminal, Maatschap Europoort Terminal (MET) and Europak
The oil storage companies operate around the clock
No restrictions regarding length and beam. Max draught is 22.55 m

For general information regarding weather the appropriate Traffic Centre sector can be contacted on VHF Channel 11

A consortium comprising global terminal operator Dubai Ports World and four major global shipping lines - French carrier CMA CGM and New World Alliance carriers MOL, Hyundai Merchant Marine and APL have been awarded the right to equip and operate the first terminal in the 16 million TEU Maasvlakte 2 development (Rotterdam World Gateway), due to start operations in 2013. It will consist of a 1900 m long deep sea quay in depth of 20 m and a 550 m long quay for inland shipping and feeder vessels
Development of two LNG terminals which will be situated near the entrance of the Beerkanaal
